# TypeScript Fundamentals

TypeScript is JavaScript with a **static type layer** that lives entirely at compile time. Think of TypeScript as a strict code reviewer who reads your code before it runs and refuses to compile anything that could blow up at runtime. The reviewer is erased when you ship — the output is plain JavaScript.

```
Your .ts source
      │
      ▼  tsc (TypeScript compiler)
 Plain .js output   ← types completely gone at runtime
      │
      ▼  Node / browser
 Runs as usual JS
```

## The Type System — a contract, not a cage

Every value in TypeScript has a **type** — a set of possible shapes. You can declare it explicitly or let TypeScript **infer** it from context.

```ts
// Explicit annotation
let age: number = 25;

// Inferred — TS figures out 'string' from the literal
let name = 'Alice';      // type: string (inferred)
name = 42;               // ✗ Error: Type 'number' is not assignable to 'string'

// Function: annotate parameters, return type is inferred
function greet(person: string): string {
  return `Hello, ${person}`;
}
```

## Primitive Types

```ts
let n: number   = 3.14;
let s: string   = 'hello';
let b: boolean  = true;
let u: undefined = undefined;
let nl: null    = null;
let big: bigint = 9007199254740991n;
let sym: symbol = Symbol('id');

// Special widened types
let anything: any    = 'start';  // escapes type system — avoid
anything = 42;                   // no error (any accepts all)
let safe: unknown    = fetch();  // must narrow before use
```

## Type Inference — TypeScript reads your code

```
let items = [1, 2, 3];     ← TypeScript sees number literals
             │
             ▼  infers
     items: number[]

let pair = [1, 'hello'];  ← mixed literals
             │
             ▼  infers
     pair: (number | string)[]

const PI = 3.14;          ← const + literal → literal type
             │
             ▼  infers
     PI: 3.14   (not 'number' — the exact value)
```

## Union and Intersection Types

```ts
// Union: either A or B
type StringOrNumber = string | number;
function format(x: StringOrNumber): string {
  return String(x);
}

// Intersection: must be both A and B simultaneously
type Named   = { name: string };
type Aged    = { age: number };
type Person  = Named & Aged;    // { name: string; age: number }

const p: Person = { name: 'Alice', age: 30 };  // must have both
```

## Type Narrowing — the detective model

Narrowing is TypeScript tracking what a type *must* be at a specific point in code based on your checks. Think of it as TypeScript playing detective: each `if` or `typeof` gives it more evidence.

```
function printId(id: string | number) {
                    ▲
                    │  wide: could be either
  if (typeof id === 'string') {
                    ▼  narrowed to string
    console.log(id.toUpperCase());  // ✓ safe
  } else {
                    ▼  narrowed to number
    console.log(id.toFixed(2));     // ✓ safe
  }
}
```

**Narrowing guards:**

```ts
typeof x === 'string'        // primitive check
x instanceof Date            // class instance check
x !== null && x !== undefined // nullish check
'prop' in x                  // shape check
Array.isArray(x)             // array check

// Custom type guard — you promise TS what the type is
function isString(x: unknown): x is string {
  return typeof x === 'string';
}
```

## Literal Types and `const` Assertions

```ts
// Without const: widened to 'string'
let direction = 'north';           // type: string

// With const: literal type
const direction = 'north';         // type: 'north'

// as const — freeze the entire shape as literals
const config = { host: 'localhost', port: 3000 } as const;
// config.host: 'localhost'  (not string)
// config.port: 3000         (not number)
// config is readonly — can't mutate
```

## `unknown` vs `any` — the safety switch

```
          any                    unknown
   ┌─────────────┐          ┌─────────────┐
   │ Accept all  │          │ Accept all  │
   │ Allow all   │          │ Must narrow │
   │ operations  │          │ before use  │
   └─────────────┘          └─────────────┘
   Turns off type           Stays type safe
   checking entirely        until proven

// any — danger zone
function riskyProcess(x: any) {
  x.doAnything();   // no error — but crashes at runtime if x has no method
}

// unknown — safe zone
function safeProcess(x: unknown) {
  x.doAnything();  // ✗ Error: can't call method on unknown
  if (typeof x === 'object' && x !== null && 'doAnything' in x) {
    (x as { doAnything: () => void }).doAnything();  // now safe
  }
}
```

## `never` — the impossible type

`never` is the type of values that can **never exist**. A function that always throws returns `never`. An exhaustive switch after all cases have been handled leaves a `never`-typed variable.

```ts
function fail(msg: string): never {
  throw new Error(msg);  // never returns normally
}

type Shape = 'circle' | 'square';
function area(s: Shape): number {
  switch (s) {
    case 'circle': return Math.PI;
    case 'square': return 1;
    default:
      const _exhaustive: never = s;  // TS error if Shape gets a new case
      return _exhaustive;
  }
}
```

## Complexity Cheatsheet

| Concept | Key rule |
|---|---|
| `let` inference | Widens to base type (e.g. `string`) |
| `const` inference | Narrows to literal type (e.g. `'north'`) |
| `any` | Turns off checking — avoid in production |
| `unknown` | Safe any — must prove type before use |
| `never` | Unreachable code marker |
| Union `A \| B` | Either A or B — narrow to use specific ops |
| Intersection `A & B` | Both A and B — adds all properties |

## Common Pitfalls
- Reaching for `any` when `unknown` would keep you safe
- Forgetting that `typeof null === 'object'` — always check `x !== null` before using `in`
- Implicit `any` in function parameters — enable `strict: true` in tsconfig to catch these
- Mutating a `const` assertion object — `as const` makes it deeply readonly at the type level
- Thinking TypeScript's types exist at runtime — they are 100% erased; `instanceof` on a TS interface fails

